Agnieszka & Karu,


In Eric's defense, I did try and call both of you on Friday arvo just
to clarify what you meant by the new rules/policy and I couldn't get
on to either of you.  Sending something out an email on a topic such
as the ICS PGRF on a  Friday afternoon afternoon is always going to
look bad, especially when you are not there to clear up any
misconceptions - such as the one I had.  Even if Friday afternoon is
the first chance you have, you may want to delay sending out such
information until Monday morning instead?


I agree that we should try and maximise our use of the MQ PGRF as this
will maximise the money into the division, which is a great thing.=20
However, I just hope that we are not moving in the direction of using
the MQ PGRF for funding essential parts of our degree and moving away
from the main aim of the MQ PGRF which is to <italic>"provide the
University=92s postgraduate research students with the means to
<bold>enhance</bold> their postgraduate research experience and
<bold>add value</bold> to their thesis"</italic>.


On a similar note, I have had no personal experience with any ICS PGRF
applications being knocked back, although I haven't really written as
many papers as I should have by now.  So, I would appreciate it if
anyone who has had an ICS PGRF application knocked back (current or
past application) because there wasn't enough money there for them to
please contact me or one of the other reps with the details so that we
can starting building up some data on this topic.  Matt, you sound
like you have some information on this.  Without these details, we
(the reps) really can't do much. =20


Cheers

James

